title_1: Ange (l') conducteur dans la dévotion chrétienne
notes_1: Edition not located.  Superbook title after Dawson and 1781 Lille edition.  Dawson says that Coret wrote several variations on this title but that the layout of the permit register suggests that these entries are for the same work.  In fact, the precise content of editions of the 'Ange conducteur' [and variant titles] evolved considerably over time and between editions: for practical purposes all variants have been treated as part of the same superbook [work] as clearly they belong to the same intellectual project.

notes_1: Edition not located. Superbook attribution not certain. Dawson assumes that all entries refer to Brignon's translation of Scupoli's 'Combat spirituel'. However, most entries under title 'Le Combat Spirituel' are grouped under a separate rubric in the source data four folios before those that can be positively linked to Brignon. However the two sets of entries form a single chronological series in the MS source data, which strongly supports his hypothesis. Nevertheless, it should be noted that other authors wrote works with similar titles.

title_1: Recueil des oraisons funebres, prononce?es par feu messire Jacques-Benigne Bossuet, Eve?que de Meaux. Nouvelle e?dition, dans laquelle on a ajoute? un pre?cis de la vie de l'auteur. Recueil des oraisons funebres, prononce?es par feu messire prononce?es par messire Esprit Fle?chier, eve?que de Ni?mes, Nouv. e?d., dans laquelle on a ajoute? un pre?cis de la vie de l'auteur.
notes_1: Edition(s) verified in worldcat. It is not clear whether they were ever published as a single volume - usually they were issued separately and that is how they are found in library catalogues. The title 'Recueil des oraisons funebres' may have covered both, but the source data says that the collection was supposed to be one volume. The edition of Bossuet's 'Oraisons' contains the following: E?loge historique de feu messire Benigne Bossuet,, eve?que de Meaux; Oraison funebre de la reine de la Grande-Bretagne; Oraison funebre de Henriette-Anne d'Angleterre, duchesse d'Orle?ans; Oraison funebre de Marie-The?re?se d'Autriche, infante d'Espagne, reine de France et de Navarre; Oraison funebre d'Anne de Gonzague de Cleves, princesse palatine; Oraison funebre de messire Michel Le Tellier, chancelier de France; Oraison funebre de Louis de Bourbon, prince de Condé. For the Flechier volume the oraisons are listed as Madame la duchesse de Montausier; Madame la duchesse d'Aiguillon; Monsieur de Turenne; Monsieur le premier pre?sident de Lamoignon; Marie Therese d'Autriche; Messire Michel Le Tellier; Madame la dauphine; Monsieur le duc de Montausier. The Imprint for Bossuet is given as: A Lyon, chez Faucheux, imprimeur-libraire quai & maison des Ce?lestins. M. DCC. LXXX. Avec permission. 227-[1] p. ; in-12; for Flechier we have Lyon : Chez Faucheux, 1780. xxix, 226 pages. It appears that the two vols may have been published separately.
title_2: Recueil des oraisons funèbres, prononcées par M. Esprit Fléchier... et par M. Jacques-Bénigne Bossuet

notes_1: Edition verified by Robert Dawson in 'French Book Trade'. title_1: Ange (l') conducteur dans la dévotion chrétienne
notes_1: Edition not located.  Superbook title after Dawson and 1781 Lille edition.  Dawson says that Coret wrote several variations on this title but that the layout of the permit register suggests that these entries are for the same work.  In fact, the precise content of editions of the 'Ange conducteur' [and variant titles] evolved considerably over time and between editions: for practical purposes all variants have been treated as part of the same superbook [work] as clearly they belong to the same intellectual project.

In fact, the precise content of editions of the 'Ange conducteur' [and variant titles] evolved considerably over time and between editions: for practical purposes all variants have been treated as part of the same superbook [work] as clearly they belong to the same intellectual project.

title_1: Ange (l') conducteur dans la dévotion chrétienne
notes_1: Edition not located.  Superbook title after Dawson and 1781 Lille edition.  Dawson says that Coret wrote several variations on this title but that the layout of the permit register suggests that these entries are for the same work.  In fact, the precise content of editions of the 'Ange conducteur' [and variant titles] evolved considerably over time and between editions: for practical purposes all variants have been treated as part of the same superbook [work] as clearly they belong to the same intellectual project.

notes_1: Edition not located. Superbook attribution not certain. Dawson assumes that all entries refer to Brignon's translation of Scupoli's 'Combat spirituel'. notes_1: Edition verified, but not actually clear whether this is the Durand-Sugère's permit edition or veuve Valade permit edition.  Dawson says that Durand-Sugère's permit probably had something to do with the editions published with the imprint Paris: Aux Dépens de la Compagnie, 1787). He seems correct in this assumption since the idref authority file for the Compagnie des libraires (Paris ; 1700?-1777?), identifies Durand-Sugère as a member of the company in 1774, though it puts the end date of this collectivity at around 1777. For this reason it seems reasonable at first sight to link Durand-Sugère to this edition, even though the idref file suggests that compagnie came to an end about 1777. However, there was also another duodecimo edition of Boileau's works with a Paris imprint in the same year (Paris : Chez les Libraires associe?s, 1787). This too appears to be a 'compagnie des libraires' imprint. As both the veuve Valade and Durand-Sugère applied for licences to print Boileau's works the previous year (1786), it is therefore impossible to be sure which edition(s) can be tied to each of them. We have assumed that one of them is the veuve Valade edition, and arbitrarily tied her in the database to  the Libraires associe?s edition and Durand-Sugère to the 'aux depens de la compagnie edition', since it seems overwhelmingly likely these are both permit editions. Both editions seem to have had 297 pages of main text.

title_1: Heures dédiées au roi contenant les prières du matin, etc
notes_1: Superbook and edition not identified.  Worldcat lists c17 edition with longer title. In the source data, this entry names two publishers. The other is Monnoyer père in Neufchâteau. On this item the name of Le Seure appears first in the source data, some of which appears to be added after it was first written. The relevant part of the entry  reads 'Le Seure l'aine, imp. a Nancy, Monnoyer Libre Imp [Libraire Imprimeur] a Neufchateau'. Dawson assumed that two licences were granted the same day, but it seems more likely that this was a joint enterprise, since the other instance of a double entry in the documents, also dated '20 novembre 1786' for some 'Heures nouvelles dédiées a la reine' also concerns the same two men. This suggests a partnership.

notes_1: Superbook and edition not identified.  Dawson suggests that it could be Saint-Cyr/Le Tourneux, 'L'Office de la sainte vierge en latin et en français' (1714). Dawson assumed that Metz was a clerical error in the source data, believing Lamort was Claude-Sigisbert Lamort, who was based in Nancy. He was unaware that Claude-Sigisbert's son Claude Lamort (1758-1828) set up as a printer in Metz in April 1784 and traded there til 1828 (see Mellot et al.). He thus wrongly reascribes this and several other editions (all post 1784) to Nancy.

notes_1: Edition identified provisionally. The other edition is a smaller format edition described in Worldcat records as in-16, which presumably correponds to another licence for an in-18 granted to Gattey in 1787. HOwever, both editions carry same imprint and may be just one edition, with an library error over format.

title_1: Ange (l') conducteur dans la dévotion chrétienne
notes_1: Edition not located.  Superbook title after Dawson and 1781 Lille edition.  Dawson says that Coret wrote several variations on this title but that the layout of the permit register suggests that these entries are for the same work.  In fact, the precise content of editions of the 'Ange conducteur' [and variant titles] evolved considerably over time and between editions: for practical purposes all variants have been treated as part of the same superbook [work] as clearly they belong to the same intellectual project.

title_1: Transitus animae revertentis ad jugum sanctum Jesu Christi
notes_1: Worldcat lists 1788 edition by this publisher but Dawson suggests this is the earlier edition.  Dawson notes that this is unusual case of a recent work from 1782 being given a permission. Dawson speculates that this 500 copy edition may have been a 'dummy' licence to compensate for the total of 1500 copies Cazamea's printed version of his licence of 20 August 1787 claimed, for the register only authorised 1000 copies.
title_2: Transitus animae revertentis ad jugum sanctum Jesu Christi
notes_2: Edition verified by Worldcat and Dawson, after permit copy. Actual date of publication and URL after Google Books, Worldcat and Dawson permit copy. Google books edition includes permission simple with same date.  Dawson notes that this is unusual case of a recent work from 1782 being given a permission. He also notes discrepancies between no. of copies on register and that printed inside copy (1500) and speculates that Cazamea was forced to apply for licence for further 500 - which is also found in registers, so the two entries of 20 August and 30 September 1787 are probably in fact for one edition of 1500 copies.
